var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"Poster.html#SiCell.jl-Poster","page":"SiCell.jl Poster","text":"(Image: SiCell Poster)","title":"SiCell.jl Poster"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Tutorials","page":"Tutorials","text":"This section provides step-by-step walkthroughs for common single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) analysis workflows using SiCell.jl.\n\n","title":"Tutorials"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#1.-Basic-Analysis-Workflow","page":"Tutorials","text":"This tutorial demonstrates the standard analysis pipeline from raw count matrices to clustered cell populations and biological interpretation.","title":"1. Basic Analysis Workflow"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Loading-Data","page":"Tutorials","text":"SiCell.jl supports commonly used single-cell data formats.\n\nusing SiCell\n\n# Load 10x Genomics output\nobj = read_10x(\"data/filtered_feature_bc_matrix/\")\n\n# Load an AnnData (.h5ad) file\n# obj = read_h5ad(\"data/dataset.h5ad\")","title":"📂 Loading Data"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Quality-Control","page":"Tutorials","text":"Calculate quality-control metrics and remove low-quality cells.\n\ncalculate_qc_metrics!(obj)\n\nfilter_cells!(\n    obj;\n    min_genes=200,\n    max_genes=5000,\n    max_mito=10.0\n)","title":"🔬 Quality Control"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Normalization-and-Feature-Selection","page":"Tutorials","text":"Normalize expression values and identify highly variable genes.\n\n# Library-size normalization followed by log transformation\nnormalize_data!(obj)\n\n# Identify highly variable genes\nfind_variable_features!(\n    obj;\n    n_features=2000\n)\n\n# Optional: scale gene expression values\nscale_data!(obj)","title":"⚖️ Normalization and Feature Selection"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Dimensionality-Reduction","page":"Tutorials","text":"Reduce the dimensionality of the dataset and construct the neighborhood graph.\n\n# Principal component analysis\nrun_pca!(obj)\n\n# Construct K-nearest-neighbor graph\nfind_neighbors!(\n    obj;\n    k=20,\n    dims=30\n)\n\n# Compute UMAP embedding\nrun_umap!(obj)","title":"📊 Dimensionality Reduction"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Clustering","page":"Tutorials","text":"Identify cellular populations using graph-based community detection.\n\nrun_clustering!(obj, k=12)\nrun_graph_clustering!(obj, method=\"label_propagation\", key=\"graph_cluster\")\nrun_graph_clustering!(obj, method=\"louvain\", key=\"graph_cluster\")\n","title":"🧩  Clustering"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Visualization","page":"Tutorials","text":"Visualize cell clusters and gene expression patterns.\n\n# Visualize clusters\ndim_plot(\n    obj,\n    reduction=\"umap\",\n    group=\"graph_cluster\"\n)\n\n# Visualize expression of a marker gene\nfeature_plot(\n    obj,\n    \"CD3D\"\n)\n\n","title":"🎨 Visualization"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#2.-Batch-Integration-with-Harmony","page":"Tutorials","text":"For datasets containing multiple samples, patients, or experimental batches, SiCell.jl provides Harmony-based batch correction and integration.\n\n# Merge datasets\nmerged_obj = merge_batches!(\n    obj1,\n    obj2;\n    batch1_name=\"Patient1\",\n    batch2_name=\"Patient2\"\n)\n\n# Standard preprocessing\ncalculate_qc_metrics!(merged_obj)\nnormalize_data!(merged_obj)\nfind_variable_features!(merged_obj)\nscale_data!(merged_obj)\nrun_pca!(merged_obj)\n\n# Harmony correction\nrun_harmony!(\n    merged_obj,\n    batch_key=\"batch\"\n)\n\n# Construct graph using Harmony embedding\nfind_neighbors!(\n    merged_obj,\n    reduction=\"harmony\"\n)\n\n# Visualization and  etc\nrun_umap!(\n    merged_obj,\n    reduction=\"harmony\"\n)\n\n\n\n","title":"2. 🔗 Batch Integration with Harmony"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#3.-Trajectory-Inference","page":"Tutorials","text":"SiCell.jl provides diffusion-based pseudotime analysis for studying continuous biological processes such as differentiation, cellular activation, and disease progression.","title":"3. 🌊 Trajectory Inference"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Diffusion-Maps","page":"Tutorials","text":"Compute a low-dimensional manifold representation suitable for trajectory analysis.\n\nrun_diffusion_map!(\n    obj;\n    n_components=10\n)","title":"Diffusion Maps"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Pseudotime","page":"Tutorials","text":"Select a biologically meaningful root cell or population and compute pseudotime.\n\n# Example using a root cell index\nroot_cell = 1\n\nrun_pseudotime!(\n    obj,\n    root_cell;\n    method=\"graph\"\n)\n\nPseudotime values are stored in:\n\nobj.meta_data.pseudotime","title":"⏱️ Pseudotime"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Visualize-Pseudotime","page":"Tutorials","text":"dim_plot(\n    obj,\n    reduction=\"umap\",\n    group=\"pseudotime\"\n)\n\n","title":"🎨 Visualize Pseudotime"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#4.-Trajectory-Uncertainty-Framework-(TUF)","page":"Tutorials","text":"Traditional pseudotime methods assign cells a position along a trajectory but do not quantify the local uncertainty associated with that trajectory.\n\nThe Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF) introduces two complementary metrics:\n\nTemporal Entropy Score (TES): quantifies temporal inconsistency among neighboring cells.\nTrajectory Divergence Score (TDS): quantifies disagreement among forward developmental directions.\n\nTogether, TES and TDS provide complementary views of local trajectory uncertainty.","title":"4. 🌱 Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF)"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Compute-TES-and-TDS","page":"Tutorials","text":"After constructing a neighborhood graph and computing pseudotime:\n\ntrajectory_uncertainty!(\n    obj;\n    pseudotime_key=\"pseudotime\",\n    reduction=\"diffusion\"\n)\n\nThe computed scores are stored in:\n\nobj.meta_data.traj_unc_tes\nobj.meta_data.traj_unc_tds","title":"🧮 Compute TES and TDS"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Visualize-TES-and-TDS","page":"Tutorials","text":"    trajectory_uncertainty_plot(obj; reduction=\"umap\", key_prefix=\"traj_unc\")","title":"🎨 Visualize TES and TDS"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#Interpreting-TUF","page":"Tutorials","text":"TES TDS Interpretation\nLow Low Stable and well-defined cellular trajectory\nHigh Low Temporal mixing or heterogeneous developmental states\nLow High Directional divergence and potential branching\nHigh High Complex transitions involving both temporal and directional ambiguity\n\n","title":"Interpreting TUF"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#5.-Differential-Expression-Analysis","page":"Tutorials","text":"Identify genes associated with specific cellular populations or states.\n\nfind_markers!(\n    obj;\n    group=\"graph_cluster\"\n)\n\nThe output includes:\n\nDifferentially expressed genes\nEffect sizes\nStatistical significance values\nMultiple-testing corrected p-values\n\n","title":"5. 🧬 Differential Expression Analysis"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#6.-Automated-Cell-Type-Annotation","page":"Tutorials","text":"SiCell.jl supports marker-based cell type annotation using Cell marker 2.\n\ndb = load_cellmarker(species=\"Hs\")\n\nannotate_clusters!(obj, markers, db,\n    species=\"Hs\",\n    min_score=0.03)\n\n","title":"6. 🏷️ Automated Cell Type Annotation"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials.html#What's-Next?","page":"Tutorials","text":"After completing the basic workflow, you can:\n\nPerform differential expression analysis to identify marker genes.\nAnnotate cellular populations using PanglaoDB.\nIntegrate multi-sample datasets with Harmony.\nStudy developmental and disease trajectories using pseudotime.\nIdentify transitional and branching states using TES and TDS.\nGenerate high quality visualizations.\n\nFor more advanced examples, consult the full API documentation and case-study notebooks.","title":"🚀 What's Next?"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#PBMC-3k-Case-Study:-End-to-End-Single-Cell-Analysis-with-SiCell.jl","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"","title":"PBMC 3k Case Study: End-to-End Single-Cell Analysis with SiCell.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#Overview","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"This case study demonstrates a complete single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) analysis workflow using SiCell.jl on the widely used 10x Genomics PBMC 3k dataset.\n\nStarting from raw count matrices, we perform:\n\nQuality control and preprocessing\nDimensionality reduction\nGraph-based clustering\nAutomated cell type annotation\nMarker gene analysis\nDifferential expression visualization\nDiffusion-based trajectory inference\nTrajectory Uncertainty Framework (TES, TDS)\n\nThis example highlights how SiCell.jl provides an integrated workflow from raw sequencing data to biologically meaningful insights.\n\n","title":"Overview"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#1.-Data-Loading-and-Quality-Control","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"The PBMC 3k dataset contains approximately 3,000 human peripheral blood mononuclear cells.\n\nAfter quality filtering, 2,643 high-quality cells were retained for downstream analysis.\n\nobj = read_10x(DATA_PATH)\n\ncalculate_qc_metrics!(obj)\n\nfilter_cells!(\n    obj,\n    min_genes=200,\n    max_mito=5.0\n)\n\n","title":"1. Data Loading and Quality Control"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#2.-Normalization-and-Feature-Selection","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"The filtered dataset was normalized and highly variable genes were identified.\n\nnormalize_data!(obj)\nfind_variable_features!(obj)\nrun_pca!(obj)\n\n","title":"2. Normalization and Feature Selection"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#3.-Clustering-and-UMAP-Visualization","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"A K-nearest-neighbor graph was constructed followed by graph-based clustering and UMAP visualization.\n\nfind_neighbors!(obj, k=30)\n\nrun_clustering!(\n    obj)\n\nrun_umap!(obj)","title":"3. Clustering and UMAP Visualization"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#Cell-Population-Structure","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"The resulting UMAP reveals clearly separated immune populations.\n\n(Image: PBMC UMAP Clusters)\n\nFigure 1. UMAP representation of PBMC cells colored by graph-based clusters.\n\n","title":"Cell Population Structure"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#4.-Automated-Cell-Type-Annotation","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"Cluster marker genes were identified and compared against CellMarker references to assign biological identities.\n\nmarkers = find_all_markers(obj, group=\"cluster\")\n\ndb = load_cellmarker(species=\"Hs\")\n\nannotate_clusters!(\n    obj,\n    markers,\n    db,\n    species=\"Hs\"\n)\n\nThe analysis identified several major immune populations:\n\nCell Type Number of Cells\nNaive CD4+ T cells 592\nActivated T cells 583\nCytotoxic CD4+ T cells 447\nFollicular B cells 337\nCD1C+ B dendritic cells 348\nCD1C-CD141- dendritic cells 325\nMegakaryocytes 11\n\n","title":"4. Automated Cell Type Annotation"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#5.-Marker-Gene-Validation","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"Expression visualization confirms expected lineage-specific markers.\n\nFor example:\n\nCD3D is enriched in T-cell populations.\nCD79A is enriched in B-cell populations.\n\nviolin_plot(\n    obj,\n    features=[\"CD3D\", \"CD79A\"],\n    group=\"cell_type\"\n)\n\n(Image: Marker Validation)\n\nFigure 2. Canonical immune markers validate automated cell-type annotation.\n\n","title":"5. Marker Gene Validation"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#6.-Differential-Expression-Analysis","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"SiCell.jl provides efficient marker detection and visualization tools.\n\nmarkers = find_all_markers(\n    obj,\n    group=\"cluster\"\n)\n\nThe resulting markers can be explored using volcano plots.\n\n(Image: Volcano Plot)\n\nFigure 3. Differentially expressed genes highlighting cluster-specific signatures.\n\n","title":"6. Differential Expression Analysis"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#7.-Population-Connectivity-Analysis","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"To investigate relationships between cellular populations, SiCell.jl computes PAGA-style connectivity graphs.\n\npaga_plot(\n    obj,\n    reduction=\"umap\",\n    cluster_col=\"cell_type\"\n)\n\nThe PBMC connectivity structure revealed strong relationships among T-cell populations, while B cells and dendritic cells formed distinct transcriptional neighborhoods.\n\n(Image: PAGA Connectivity)\n\nFigure 4. Population-level connectivity graph between annotated immune cell types.\n\n","title":"7. Population Connectivity Analysis"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#8.-Diffusion-Based-Trajectory-Inference","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"To investigate continuous cellular transitions, a diffusion map was computed and pseudotime was initialized from the Naive CD4+ T-cell population.\n\nrun_diffusion_map!(obj)\n\nrun_pseudotime!(\n    obj,\n    root_type,\n    cluster_col=\"cell_type\"\n)\n\nPseudotime reconstruction reveals gradual transitions across immune states.\n\n(Image: Pseudotime UMAP)\n\nFigure 5. UMAP colored by diffusion pseudotime.\n\n","title":"8. Diffusion-Based Trajectory Inference"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#9.-Trajectory-Uncertainty-Framework-(TUF)","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"Traditional pseudotime provides a single ordering of cells but does not indicate whether the local trajectory is well-defined or ambiguous.\n\nSiCell.jl introduces the Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF), composed of:\n\nTemporal Entropy Score (TES) — quantifies local temporal mixing.\nTrajectory Divergence Score (TDS) — quantifies disagreement among forward developmental directions.\nLocal Progression Score (LPS) — measures local progression tendency along the trajectory.\n\ntrajectory_uncertainty!(\n    obj,\n    key_prefix=\"traj_unc\"\n)","title":"9. Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF)"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#Global-Summary","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"Metric Mean Maximum\nTES 0.061 0.132\nTDS 0.216 0.932\n\n","title":"Global Summary"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#Cell-Type-Level-Trajectory-Uncertainty","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"Averaging uncertainty metrics across cell populations provides insight into their trajectory behavior.\n\nCell Type TES TDS\nActivated T cells 0.068 0.281\nNaive CD4+ T cells 0.064 0.362\nCytotoxic CD4+ T cells 0.062 0.194\nDendritic cells ~0.06 0.09–0.13\nFollicular B cells 0.046 0.092\n\nNotably, T-cell populations exhibited elevated TDS values, suggesting greater diversity in potential future transcriptional directions compared with more stable B-cell populations.\n\n\n\n(Image: Trajectory Uncertainty)\n\nFigure 6. TES, TDS, and LPS visualized across the PBMC manifold.\n\n","title":"Cell-Type-Level Trajectory Uncertainty"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_pbmc3k.html#Conclusion","page":"PBMC3K Workflow","text":"This case study demonstrates how SiCell.jl integrates all major components of modern single-cell analysis within a unified Julia framework.\n\nUsing a single workflow, we:\n\nProcessed raw 10x Genomics data.\nIdentified biologically meaningful immune populations.\nValidated annotations through canonical marker expression.\nCharacterized population relationships using connectivity analysis.\nReconstructed continuous cellular trajectories.\nQuantified trajectory ambiguity using the novel TUF framework.\n\nSiCell.jl enables researchers to move from raw sequencing data to biological insight using a high-performance and reproducible analysis environment.\n\n\n\nComplete analysis script: examples/pbmc3k_full_pipeline.jl","title":"Conclusion"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#Case-Study:-Breast-Cancer-Tumor-Microenvironment-Analysis-with-SiCell.jl","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"","title":"Case Study: Breast Cancer Tumor Microenvironment Analysis with SiCell.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#Overview","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"This case study demonstrates the application of SiCell.jl to a large-scale breast cancer single-cell RNA sequencing dataset containing 34,144 cells. The analysis covers the complete workflow from preprocessing and cell type annotation to trajectory inference and the Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF).\n\nThe goal is to identify cellular populations within the tumor microenvironment, reconstruct potential developmental transitions, and quantify regions of cellular plasticity and lineage ambiguity using Temporal Entropy Score (TES), Trajectory Divergence Score (TDS), and Local Progression Score ().\n\n","title":"Overview"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#1.-Cell-Population-Identification","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"After quality control, normalization, dimensionality reduction, and clustering, SiCell identified eight initial clusters.\n\nMarker-based annotation using the CellMarker database revealed the following major cell populations:\n\nCell Type Number of Cells\nPodocyte 8,486\nDCLK1+ progenitor cells 5,660\nLeukocytes 5,511\nCancer-associated fibroblasts 3,916\nBasal epithelial cells 2,319\nUnknown populations 8,252\n\nThe presence of multiple Unknown populations highlights the complexity of the tumor microenvironment and may represent poorly characterized, transitional, or disease-specific cell states.\n\n","title":"1. Cell Population Identification"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#UMAP-Visualization-of-Annotated-Cell-Types","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"(Image: Breast cancer cell type annotation)\n\nUMAP embedding colored by CellMarker-based cell type annotations. Distinct immune, stromal, epithelial, and progenitor-like populations can be observed across the tumor landscape.\n\n","title":"UMAP Visualization of Annotated Cell Types"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#2.-Marker-Gene-Characterization","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"Differential expression analysis identified cluster-specific marker genes that define the molecular identity of individual populations.\n\nRepresentative markers included:\n\nCYP4F8\nINHBA\nRGS16\nADGRD2\nOVCH2\nIRX4\nHPN\nLRRC31\nPODXL\nPTPRC\n\nThese genes provide molecular signatures distinguishing tumor-associated fibroblasts, immune populations, epithelial states, and other specialized cellular compartments.\n\n","title":"2. Marker Gene Characterization"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#Feature-Expression-Example","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"(Image: CYP4F8 expression across cells)\n\nFeature plot showing the expression pattern of the marker gene CYP4F8 across the breast cancer cellular landscape.\n\n","title":"Feature Expression Example"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#3.-Connectivity-Analysis-of-the-Tumor-Microenvironment","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"SiCell generated a PAGA-style connectivity graph to summarize relationships between major cell populations.\n\nStrong connectivity was observed between several stromal and progenitor-associated populations, including:\n\nCancer-associated fibroblasts ↔ Podocytes\nPodocytes ↔ DCLK1+ progenitor cells\nPodocytes ↔ Unknown populations\n\nThese connections suggest potential transcriptional similarity or shared transitional states between different cellular compartments.\n\n","title":"3. Connectivity Analysis of the Tumor Microenvironment"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#Cell-Population-Connectivity-Graph","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"(Image: Cell type connectivity graph)\n\nPopulation-level connectivity graph showing transcriptional relationships between annotated cell types.\n\n","title":"Cell Population Connectivity Graph"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#4.-Diffusion-Based-Trajectory-Inference","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"To investigate continuous cellular transitions, a diffusion map was constructed using the nearest-neighbor graph.\n\nA DCLK1+ progenitor population was selected as the trajectory root due to its stem-like characteristics.\n\nDiffusion pseudotime ordering revealed how cells transition away from this progenitor-like state toward more differentiated transcriptional programs.\n\n","title":"4. Diffusion-Based Trajectory Inference"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#5.-Trajectory-Uncertainty-Framework-(TUF)","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"Traditional pseudotime methods assign a trajectory position to each cell but do not quantify whether the local trajectory is stable or ambiguous.\n\nSiCell's TUF addresses this using three complementary metrics:\n\nTES (Temporal Entropy Score)   Measures local temporal mixing between neighboring cells.\nTDS (Trajectory Divergence Score)   Measures disagreement between forward developmental directions and identifies potential branching regions.\n\n","title":"5. Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF)"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#Global-Trajectory-Uncertainty","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"Across 34,144 cells:\n\nMetric Mean Maximum\nTES 0.054 0.112\nTDS 0.247 0.997\n\nThe high maximum TDS value suggests the presence of strongly divergent regions within the tumor trajectory landscape.\n\n","title":"Global Trajectory Uncertainty"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#TUF-Visualization","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"(Image: Trajectory uncertainty map)\n\nVisualization of TES, TDS across the cellular manifold. High uncertainty regions may correspond to cell-state transitions, branching trajectories, or plastic tumor populations.\n\n","title":"TUF Visualization"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#6.-Cell-Type-Level-Trajectory-Uncertainty","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"Average uncertainty scores revealed differences in cellular plasticity between populations.\n\nCell Type Mean TES Mean TDS\nDCLK1+ progenitor 0.055 0.238\nPodocyte 0.055 0.241\nCancer-associated fibroblast 0.054 0.293\nBasal epithelial 0.054 0.253\nUnknown 0.053 0.215\nLeukocyte 0.052 0.278\n\nNotably, cancer-associated fibroblasts exhibited the highest average TDS, indicating greater directional heterogeneity and potential involvement in dynamic remodeling of the tumor microenvironment.\n\n","title":"6. Cell-Type Level Trajectory Uncertainty"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#7.-Validation-of-High-Uncertainty-Regions","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"Cells within the top 5% of TES scores were extracted and analyzed using differential expression.\n\nThe most enriched genes included:\n\nGene Biological Association\nAEBP1 Extracellular matrix remodeling\nCOL5A1 Collagen organization\nCOL6A3 Stromal activation\nDCN Fibroblast identity\nCCN2 Tissue remodeling and fibrosis\nFN1 Cell adhesion and migration\nELN Extracellular matrix organization\n\nThe enrichment of extracellular matrix and stromal remodeling genes supports the biological relevance of high-TES regions.\n\n","title":"7. Validation of High-Uncertainty Regions"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#High-Uncertainty-Cell-Localization","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"(Image: Top 5 percent uncertainty cells)\n\nCells with the highest TES scores highlighted on the UMAP embedding. These regions may represent highly plastic cellular states and active tumor remodeling zones.\n\n","title":"High-Uncertainty Cell Localization"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#8.-Relationship-Between-TUF-Metrics","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"Correlation analysis showed that the three uncertainty measures capture related but distinct biological properties.\n\nComparison Correlation\nTES ↔ TDS 0.313\nTES ↔ 0.262\nTDS ↔ 0.763\n\nThe moderate TES–TDS correlation demonstrates that temporal mixing and directional divergence provide complementary information rather than measuring the same phenomenon.\n\n","title":"8. Relationship Between TUF Metrics"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#Biological-Insights","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"This analysis demonstrates that SiCell can move beyond traditional clustering and pseudotime analysis by identifying regions of cellular instability and potential fate transitions.\n\nKey observations include:\n\nDCLK1+ progenitor cells display elevated trajectory uncertainty, consistent with a more plastic and less committed cellular state.\nCancer-associated fibroblasts exhibit the strongest directional divergence, suggesting dynamic remodeling behavior.\nHigh-TES cells are enriched for extracellular matrix and stromal activation genes such as COL5A1, COL6A3, CCN2, and FN1.\nTES, TDS  capture complementary aspects of tumor heterogeneity.\n\n","title":"Biological Insights"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_breast_cancer.html#Conclusion","page":"Breast Cancer Analysis","text":"Using a single integrated workflow, SiCell.jl transformed a 34,144-cell breast cancer dataset into interpretable biological insights.\n\nThe combination of clustering, automated annotation, trajectory inference, and the Trajectory Uncertainty Framework enables researchers to identify not only where cells are along a trajectory, but also how confidently that trajectory can be interpreted.\n\nThis provides a powerful framework for studying tumor plasticity, cellular transitions, and the dynamic organization of complex tissues.\n\n\n\nComplete analysis script: examples/case_study_breast_cancer.jl","title":"Conclusion"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Visualization-and-Biological-Interpretation","page":"Visualizations","text":"One of the primary goals of SiCell.jl is to transform complex single-cell datasets into clear and interpretable biological insights through high-quality visualizations.\n\nFrom exploratory analysis and cell-type identification to trajectory analysis and uncertainty mapping, SiCell provides a comprehensive visualization framework designed for both computational scientists and experimental biologists.\n\n","title":"🎨 Visualization & Biological Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#UMAP-Embeddings","page":"Visualizations","text":"UMAP provides a two-dimensional representation of the cellular transcriptional landscape, preserving local relationships between cells.\n\nrun_umap!(obj)\n\ndim_plot(\n    obj,\n    group=\"cell_type\"\n)\n\nTypical applications include:\n\nIdentifying major cell populations\nVisualizing cellular heterogeneity\nAssessing batch integration quality\nInspecting quality-control effects","title":"🧭 UMAP Embeddings"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Biological-Interpretation","page":"Visualizations","text":"Distinct islands suggest transcriptionally distinct cellular populations.\nContinuous gradients often indicate differentiation or state transitions.\nMixed regions may represent transitional or plastic cellular states.\n\n","title":"Biological Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Clustering-Visualizations","page":"Visualizations","text":"SiCell supports both graph-based and centroid-based approaches for identifying cellular populations.","title":"🧩 Clustering Visualizations"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Graph-Based-Clustering","page":"Visualizations","text":"run_graph_clustering!(obj)\n\ndim_plot(\n    obj,\n    group=\"graph_cluster\"\n)\n\nGraph-based clustering is particularly useful for:\n\nDetecting rare populations\nIdentifying subtle cellular substructures\nDiscovering previously unrecognized biological states","title":"Graph-Based Clustering"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#K-Means-Clustering","page":"Visualizations","text":"run_kmeans_clustering!(obj, k=8)\n\ndim_plot(\n    obj,\n    group=\"cluster\"\n)\n\nK-means provides:\n\nRapid exploratory analysis\nScalable clustering for large datasets\nBenchmark comparison against graph-based methods\n\n","title":"K-Means Clustering"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Cell-Type-Annotation","page":"Visualizations","text":"Cell populations can be automatically annotated using marker references from PanglaoDB.\n\nannotate_cells!(\n    obj;\n    database=\"PanglaoDB\"\n)\n\ndim_plot(\n    obj,\n    group=\"cell_type\"\n)","title":"🏷️ Cell Type Annotation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Biological-Interpretation-2","page":"Visualizations","text":"Automated annotation enables rapid identification of:\n\nImmune populations\nStromal populations\nEpithelial populations\nEndothelial populations\nDisease-associated cellular states\n\nCells labeled as Unknown may represent poorly characterized, rare, or disease-specific transcriptional programs.\n\n","title":"Biological Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Feature-Plots","page":"Visualizations","text":"Feature plots visualize the spatial distribution of individual genes across the cellular manifold.\n\nfeature_plot(obj, \"CD3D\")\n\nCommon applications include:\n\nValidating marker genes\nConfirming cell identities\nInvestigating pathway activity\nIdentifying potential biomarkers\n\nExample questions:\n\nWhich populations express a gene of interest?\nIs expression restricted to a specific state?\nDoes expression follow a developmental trajectory?\n\n","title":"🧬 Feature Plots"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Violin-Plots","page":"Visualizations","text":"Violin plots compare gene expression distributions across cellular groups.\n\nviolin_plot(\n    obj,\n    \"MS4A1\",\n    group=\"cell_type\"\n)\n\nThey are useful for:\n\nMarker validation\nInterpreting differential expression results\nCreating publication-quality figures\n\n","title":"📊 Violin Plots"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Heatmaps","page":"Visualizations","text":"Heatmaps summarize gene-expression patterns across clusters or annotated cell types.\n\nheatmap_markers(obj)\n\nTypical applications:\n\nCluster characterization\nCell-type discovery\nMarker comparison\nSupplementary figure generation\n\n","title":"🔥 Heatmaps"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Volcano-Plots","page":"Visualizations","text":"Volcano plots visualize differential-expression results by combining effect size and statistical significance.\n\nvolcano_plot(markers)\n\nThey are valuable for:\n\nPrioritizing marker genes\nDiscovering candidate biomarkers\nComparing transcriptional changes between populations\n\n","title":"🌋 Volcano Plots"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Diffusion-Pseudotime","page":"Visualizations","text":"SiCell implements diffusion-based trajectory inference to reconstruct continuous biological processes.\n\nrun_diffusion_map!(obj)\n\nrun_pseudotime!(obj, root_cell)","title":"🌊 Diffusion Pseudotime"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Biological-Applications","page":"Visualizations","text":"Developmental differentiation\nCellular activation\nResponse to environmental stimuli\nDisease progression and tumor evolution","title":"Biological Applications"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Interpretation","page":"Visualizations","text":"Cells close to the chosen root state have low pseudotime values, while progressively differentiated or altered states have higher pseudotime values.\n\n","title":"Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Trajectory-Uncertainty-Framework-(TUF)","page":"Visualizations","text":"Traditional pseudotime assigns a position along a trajectory but does not quantify whether the local trajectory structure is consistent or ambiguous.\n\nThe Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF) provides two complementary measurements:\n\nTES (Temporal Entropy Score) identifies neighborhoods containing cells from heterogeneous temporal states.\nTDS (Trajectory Divergence Score) identifies regions where forward developmental directions diverge.\n\nTogether, TES and TDS reveal different forms of local trajectory uncertainty.","title":"🌱 Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF)"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Visualizing-TES-and-TDS","page":"Visualizations","text":"trajectory_uncertainty_plot(obj; reduction=\"umap\", key_prefix=\"traj_unc\")\n","title":"Visualizing TES and TDS"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Biological-Interpretation-3","page":"Visualizations","text":"","title":"Biological Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#High-TES","page":"Visualizations","text":"May indicate:\n\nTransitional cellular states\nTemporal mixing of developmental programs\nCellular plasticity or reprogramming","title":"High TES"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#High-TDS","page":"Visualizations","text":"May indicate:\n\nBranch points\nCompeting lineage trajectories\nDivergent cell-state transitions","title":"High TDS"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Combined-Interpretation","page":"Visualizations","text":"TES TDS Interpretation\nLow Low Stable, well-defined trajectory\nHigh Low Temporal heterogeneity without strong directional divergence\nLow High Directional branching or fate divergence\nHigh High Complex transitions involving multiple temporal and directional programs\n\n","title":"Combined Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Connectivity-and-Lineage-Graphs","page":"Visualizations","text":"Population-level relationships can be visualized using PAGA-style connectivity graphs.\n\nplot_paga(obj)","title":"🕸️ Connectivity & Lineage Graphs"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Interpretation-2","page":"Visualizations","text":"Nodes represent cell populations.\nEdges represent transcriptional connectivity between populations.\nStronger connections suggest closer developmental or functional relationships.\n\nThese graphs provide a high-level overview of tissue organization and potential lineage relationships.\n\n","title":"Interpretation"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Building-a-Biological-Story","page":"Visualizations","text":"SiCell visualizations are designed to work together as a complete analytical workflow:\n\nUMAP visualization reveals cellular organization.\nClustering identifies discrete populations.\nCell-type annotation assigns biological identity.\nFeature plots validate markers and pathways.\nDifferential expression identifies molecular drivers.\nPseudotime reconstructs continuous processes.\nTES and TDS highlight uncertain, transitional, and branching regions.\n\nTogether, these analyses transform raw sequencing counts into biologically meaningful hypotheses.\n\n","title":"🎯 Building a Biological Story"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Complete-Analysis-Workflow","page":"Visualizations","text":"(Image: SiCell.jl Analysis Pipeline) Overview of the SiCell.jl Analysis Pipeline\n\n","title":"📈 Complete Analysis Workflow"},{"category":"section","location":"Visualizations.html#Philosophy","page":"Visualizations","text":"SiCell is built around a simple principle:\n\nSingle-cell analysis should not stop at computation — it should accelerate biological discovery.\n\nEvery visualization in SiCell.jl is designed to help researchers move efficiently from raw data to interpretable biological insights while maintaining reproducibility and scalability.","title":"Philosophy"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#SiCell.jl","page":"Home","text":"(Image: SiCell Logo)\n\nA high-performance Julia framework for single-cell RNA sequencing analysis and trajectory uncertainty quantification.\n\nSiCell.jl is a Julia-native toolkit for end-to-end single-cell transcriptomics analysis. It provides efficient implementations of core scRNA-seq workflows including preprocessing, dimensionality reduction, clustering, differential expression, trajectory analysis, and biological interpretation.\n\nIn addition to a complete analysis workflow, SiCell.jl introduces the Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF), a novel methodology that decomposes trajectory uncertainty into two complementary components:\n\nTemporal Entropy Score (TES) — quantifies local temporal inconsistency and cellular state mixing.\nTrajectory Divergence Score (TDS) — quantifies directional ambiguity and potential lineage divergence.\n\nTogether, TES and TDS provide a new perspective on cellular plasticity, transitional states, and developmental complexity.\n\n","title":"SiCell.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Why-SiCell.jl?","page":"Home","text":"Single-cell datasets continue to increase dramatically in scale and complexity. SiCell.jl leverages Julia's performance-oriented design to enable fast, memory-efficient, and reproducible analysis of large single-cell datasets.","title":"Why SiCell.jl?"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Key-Features","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Key Features"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#High-Performance-Data-Processing","page":"Home","text":"Native support for 10x Genomics, AnnData (.h5ad), and 10x HDF5 (.h5) formats.\nEfficient sparse matrix computations.\nMulti-threaded implementations of computationally intensive operations.\nScalable workflows designed for modern single-cell atlases.\n\n","title":"🚀 High-Performance Data Processing"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Complete-Single-Cell-Analysis-Workflow","page":"Home","text":"","title":"🔬 Complete Single-Cell Analysis Workflow"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Preprocessing","page":"Home","text":"Quality control metrics and filtering.\nLibrary-size normalization.\nHighly variable gene selection.\nFeature scaling.","title":"Preprocessing"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Batch-Correction-and-Integration","page":"Home","text":"Harmony integration.\nBBKNN batch correction.","title":"Batch Correction and Integration"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Dimensionality-Reduction","page":"Home","text":"Principal Component Analysis (PCA).\nUMAP.\nDiffusion Maps.","title":"Dimensionality Reduction"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Clustering","page":"Home","text":"Graph-based Louvain clustering.\nK-means clustering.\nEfficient K-nearest-neighbor graph construction.\n\n","title":"Clustering"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Cell-Identity-and-Differential-Expression","page":"Home","text":"","title":"🧬 Cell Identity and Differential Expression"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Cell-Type-Annotation","page":"Home","text":"Marker-based annotation using PanglaoDB.\nJaccard similarity scoring for robust cell identity assignment.","title":"Cell Type Annotation"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Differential-Expression","page":"Home","text":"Fast Wilcoxon rank-sum testing.\nMultiple testing correction.\nAutomated marker gene discovery.\n\n","title":"Differential Expression"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Trajectory-Analysis-and-Trajectory-Uncertainty-Framework-(TUF)","page":"Home","text":"SiCell.jl provides graph-based trajectory inference using diffusion pseudotime and introduces the Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF).\n\nUnlike conventional pseudotime methods that only provide an ordering of cells, TUF quantifies the local uncertainty surrounding each cellular state.","title":"🌱 Trajectory Analysis and Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF)"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Temporal-Entropy-Score-(TES)","page":"Home","text":"TES measures how heterogeneous the developmental states are within a cell's local neighborhood.\n\nHigh TES indicates:\n\nTemporal mixing.\nTransitional cellular states.\nIncreased local heterogeneity.\n\n","title":"Temporal Entropy Score (TES)"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Trajectory-Divergence-Score-(TDS)","page":"Home","text":"TDS measures disagreement among forward developmental directions.\n\nHigh TDS indicates:\n\nLineage bifurcation.\nMultiple possible developmental directions.\nIncreased trajectory ambiguity.\n\n\n\nTUF is independent of the trajectory inference algorithm and can be applied to pseudotime estimates generated by different methods.\n\n","title":"Trajectory Divergence Score (TDS)"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Visualization","page":"Home","text":"SiCell.jl includes publication-quality visualization tools:\n\nUMAP and PCA embeddings.\nFeature expression plots.\nViolin plots.\nVolcano plots.\nTrajectory uncertainty maps.\nTES/TDS visualization.\nPAGA-style trajectory graphs.\n\n","title":"🎨 Visualization"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Features-Overview","page":"Home","text":"(Image: SiCell.jl Core Capabilities and Analysis Pipeline)\n\nOverview of the SiCell.jl capabilities\n\n","title":"Features Overview"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Installation","page":"Home","text":"Install directly from GitHub:\n\nusing Pkg\n\nPkg.add(url=\"https://github.com/yourusername/SiCell.jl.git\")\n\nLoad the package:\n\nusing SiCell\n\n","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Quick-Start","page":"Home","text":"using SiCell\n\n# Load data\nobj = read_h5ad(\"dataset.h5ad\")\n\n# Preprocessing\ncalculate_qc_metrics!(obj)\nfilter_cells!(obj)\nnormalize_data!(obj)\nfind_variable_features!(obj)\n\n# Dimensionality reduction\nrun_pca!(obj)\nfind_neighbors!(obj)\nrun_umap!(obj)\n\n# Clustering\nrun_graph_clustering!(obj)\n\n# Trajectory analysis\nrun_diffusion_map!(obj)\nrun_pseudotime!(obj, root_cell, method=\"graph\")\n\n# Compute trajectory uncertainty\ntrajectory_uncertainty!(obj)\n\n# Visualization\ntrajectory_uncertainty_plot(obj)\n\n","title":"Quick Start"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Analysis-Pipeline","page":"Home","text":"(Image: SiCell.jl Analysis Pipeline)","title":"Analysis Pipeline"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#*Overview-of-the-SiCell.jl-Analysis-Pipeline*","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Overview of the SiCell.jl Analysis Pipeline"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Design-Principles","page":"Home","text":"SiCell.jl is built around three central principles:","title":"Design Principles"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Performance-First","page":"Home","text":"Efficient algorithms optimized for large-scale single-cell datasets.","title":"⚡ Performance First"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Biological-Insight","page":"Home","text":"Methods designed to reveal meaningful cellular states, transitions, and regulatory programs.","title":"🧬 Biological Insight"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Julia-Native","page":"Home","text":"A clean, idiomatic Julia API with minimal overhead and direct access to high-performance scientific computing.\n\n","title":"🟣 Julia Native"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Documentation","page":"Home","text":"Comprehensive tutorials, examples, and API documentation are available in the project documentation.\n\n","title":"Documentation"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Citation","page":"Home","text":"If you use SiCell.jl in your research, please cite:\n\nSiCell.jl: A Julia framework for single-cell analysis and trajectory uncertainty quantification.\n\n(Manuscript in preparation.)\n\n","title":"Citation"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Related-Software","page":"Home","text":"Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF) is also available as a Python package compatible with Scanpy/AnnData workflows.\n\n","title":"Related Software"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#Contributing","page":"Home","text":"Contributions, bug reports, feature requests, and discussions are welcome. Please open an issue or submit a pull request.\n\n","title":"Contributing"},{"category":"section","location":"index.html#License","page":"Home","text":"SiCell.jl is released under the MIT License.","title":"License"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#Case-Study:-Revealing-Hidden-Cellular-Plasticity-in-Glioblastoma-with-TUF","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"","title":"Case Study: Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#Overview","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"Understanding cellular transitions within tumors is a major challenge in single-cell analysis. Traditional pseudotime methods assign cells along a developmental trajectory but do not indicate whether local trajectory structure is stable, transitional, or directionally ambiguous.\n\nUsing SiCell.jl, we analyzed a glioblastoma (GBM) single-cell RNA sequencing dataset and applied the Trajectory Uncertainty Framework (TUF) to quantify two complementary aspects of cellular uncertainty:\n\nTemporal Entropy Score (TES): local heterogeneity of neighboring cells along pseudotime.\nTrajectory Divergence Score (TDS): disagreement between potential forward developmental directions.\n\nTogether, these metrics reveal stable states, transitional populations, and regions of cellular plasticity that are not captured by pseudotime alone.\n\n","title":"Overview"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#1.-Standard-Single-Cell-Processing","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"The dataset was processed using the standard SiCell.jl workflow:\n\nusing SiCell\n\ncalculate_qc_metrics!(obj)\nfilter_cells!(obj)\nnormalize_data!(obj)\n\nfind_variable_features!(obj)\nrun_pca!(obj)\n\nfind_neighbors!(obj)\nrun_umap!(obj)\n\nrun_graph_clustering!(obj)\n\nThe resulting UMAP reveals the major transcriptional populations within the GBM microenvironment.\n\n(Image: GBM UMAP Cell Types)\n\nFigure 1. UMAP embedding showing major cellular populations identified in the GBM dataset.\n\n","title":"1. Standard Single-Cell Processing"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#2.-Diffusion-Based-Trajectory-Analysis","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"To model continuous changes in cellular state, diffusion maps and graph-based pseudotime were computed:\n\nrun_diffusion_map!(obj)\n\nrun_pseudotime!(\n    obj,\n    root_cell,\n    method=\"graph\"\n)\n\nPseudotime reconstructs the progression of cellular states but does not provide information about uncertainty.\n\n(Image: GBM Pseudotime)\n\nFigure 2. Diffusion pseudotime reveals the progression of cellular states across the GBM landscape.\n\n","title":"2. Diffusion-Based Trajectory Analysis"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#3.-Quantifying-Trajectory-Uncertainty","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"TUF was applied directly on the pseudotime graph:\n\ntrajectory_uncertainty!(obj)\n\nThis produces two complementary measurements:","title":"3. Quantifying Trajectory Uncertainty"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#Temporal-Entropy-Score-(TES)-and-Trajectory-Divergence-Score-(TDS)","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"TES identifies regions where neighboring cells occupy heterogeneous positions along the trajectory.\n\nTDS measures disagreement in local forward developmental directions.\n\n trajectory_uncertainty_plot(obj, title=\"Trajectory Uncertainty Framework — Glioblastoma\")\n\n(Image: GBM TES)\n\nFigure 3. TES highlights regions of elevated temporal heterogeneity, suggesting transitional or plastic cellular states. TDS identifies regions where cells have multiple potential future trajectory directions\n\n\n\n","title":"Temporal Entropy Score (TES) and Trajectory Divergence Score (TDS)"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#4.-TES-and-TDS-Capture-Distinct-Biological-Signals","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"Although both metrics quantify trajectory uncertainty, they represent different biological phenomena.\n\nHigh TES, low TDS: heterogeneous populations occupying mixed developmental stages.\nLow TES, high TDS: branch points or competing developmental paths.\nHigh TES and high TDS: highly dynamic states with both temporal mixing and directional ambiguity.\n\nThis separation allows researchers to distinguish different forms of cellular plasticity that would otherwise appear similar using pseudotime alone.\n\n","title":"4. TES and TDS Capture Distinct Biological Signals"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#5.-Biological-Interpretation-of-High-Uncertainty-States","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"Cells with elevated TES were associated with stress-response and adaptive programs, including:\n\nHypoxia\nTNF-α/NF-κB signaling\nApoptosis\nEpithelial–mesenchymal transition (EMT)\n\nThese pathways suggest that high TES regions correspond to environmentally driven cellular adaptation rather than simple developmental progression.\n\nTDS identified distinct biological processes associated with changes in trajectory directionality, indicating that temporal heterogeneity and lineage divergence represent separate dimensions of cellular state transitions.\n\n","title":"5. Biological Interpretation of High-Uncertainty States"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#6.-Key-Findings","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"This analysis demonstrates how TUF extends conventional trajectory analysis:\n\nMethod Information Provided\nPseudotime Ordering of cells along a trajectory\nTES Temporal heterogeneity and cellular plasticity\nTDS Directional ambiguity and potential branching\nTES + TDS Comprehensive characterization of trajectory uncertainty\n\nBy combining these complementary measurements, SiCell.jl enables researchers to move beyond trajectory reconstruction and identify biologically meaningful transition states.\n\n","title":"6. Key Findings"},{"category":"section","location":"case_studies/case_study_glioblastoma.html#Reproducibility","page":"Revealing Hidden Cellular Plasticity in Glioblastoma with TUF","text":"The complete analysis workflow, including preprocessing, trajectory inference, uncertainty quantification, and visualization, can be reproduced using the SiCell.jl tutorials and API documentation.\n\nComplete analysis script: examples/case_study_glioblastoma.jl","title":"Reproducibility"}]
}
